WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.061
Patient Admission and Setup


00:00:02.061 --> 00:00:03.045
1.


00:00:03.045 --> 00:00:07.358
Warm Welcome**: Greet each patient with a friendly smile and address them by name.


00:00:07.358 --> 00:00:13.444
Introduce yourself by stating your role and purpose, while maintaining eye contact to build trust and rapport.


00:00:13.444 --> 00:00:14.214
2.


00:00:14.214 --> 00:00:20.630
Secure Personal Belongings**: Politely ask the patient to place their personal items, such as bags, coats,


00:00:20.630 --> 00:00:25.283
or any valuables, in a designated safe area that is easily accessible and visible during their


00:00:25.283 --> 00:00:26.060
visit.


00:00:26.060 --> 00:00:28.934
This ensures both safety and peace of mind.


00:00:28.934 --> 00:00:29.885
3.


00:00:29.885 --> 00:00:35.349
Engage in Conversation**: Begin a light, friendly conversation to help the patient feel at ease.


00:00:35.349 --> 00:00:41.746
Ask about their day or any recent experiences to create a comfortable environment that encourages open communication.


00:00:41.746 --> 00:00:42.741
4.


00:00:42.741 --> 00:00:47.982
Explain Procedures in Detail**: Clearly outline what the patient can expect throughout their visit.


00:00:47.982 --> 00:00:52.765
Describe each procedure step-by-step and encourage the patient to ask questions, addressing


00:00:52.765 --> 00:00:56.573
any concerns they may have to ensure they feel informed and secure.


00:00:56.573 --> 00:00:58.341
Positioning the Patient**:


00:00:58.341 --> 00:01:02.084
Upright Position**: This position is typically used when the patient is entering


00:01:02.084 --> 00:01:06.389
the office, being dismissed after their appointment, or when taking radiographs and


00:01:06.389 --> 00:01:07.518
impressions.


00:01:07.518 --> 00:01:11.420
It allows for easy interaction and is comfortable for brief periods.


00:01:11.420 --> 00:01:16.737
Supine Position**: The most common position used for a wide variety of dental procedures.


00:01:16.737 --> 00:01:23.611
In this position, the patient lies back on the dental chair, ensuring they remain relaxed and stable throughout the treatment.


00:01:23.611 --> 00:01:30.912
Subsupine Position**: In cases of medical emergencies, this position is utilized where the patientâ€™s head is lowered below their feet.


00:01:30.912 --> 00:01:36.895
This posture can help improve blood flow to the brain during emergencies and is crucial for timely medical assistance.

